{"code":1,"isDone":false,"toInsertArticleList":[{"createdTime":"2020-09-05 15:07:28","updatedTime":"2020-09-05 15:07:28","title":"ProxySQL Query Rules: Notes From Production","link":"https://blog.pythian.com/?p=108050","description":"<div class=\"l-submain\">\n <div class=\"l-submain-h g-html i-cf\"> \n  <p>After spending four years working with ProxySQL in production, I’ve learned a few interesting lessons about interpreting and processing query rules. I hope to save you some time (and avoid wrong turns) with this summary of ProxySQL query rules.</p> \n  <h4></h4> \n  <p><a href=\"https://proxysql.com/\">ProxySQL</a> query engine is very powerful and supports the building of complex rule sets. These can be used to route traffic to backend MySQL instances, rewrite queries, and for <a href=\"https://proxysql.com/documentation/mirroring/\">traffic mirroring,</a> among other use cases.</p> \n  <p>When the rule set is short and simple, you can easily understand what the outcome for a certain query would be. However, for complex sets or combined scenarios, you need a deeper understanding of the engine logic.</p> \n  <h3>Note 1: Rules are processed in rule_id order</h3> \n  <p>It might seem like a trivial start, but during testing or implementation, it’s not uncommon to delete or insert the rules without taking the id into consideration. Furthermore, in more mature environments, it’s also common to have disabled rules allocating ids. This can cause the runtime set to be less linear than with newer environments. Unless different chains were implemented, rules are processed based on the id, from lowest to highest.</p> \n  <h3>Note 2: Things to consider when using flagIN / flagOUT to create rule chains</h3> \n  <p>Sometimes you need the query engine to take different paths depending on certain conditions, and you need to create rule chains for that purpose. The documentation says that you can set a <strong>flagOUT</strong> value for a rule so that only those with a matching <strong>flagIN </strong>are evaluated next. What is not always clear is that a query is only marked with <strong>flagOUT</strong> if the query matches the rule in question. Also:</p> \n  <ul> \n   <li>Remember that only rules with <strong>flagIN</strong> equal to 0 are considered at the beginning. \n    <div class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"> \n     <img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-108415\" class=\"wp-image-108415 size-full\" src=\"https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules1.png\" alt=\"Trivial ruleset\" width=\"528\" height=\"127\" srcset=\"https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules1.png 528w, https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules1-465x112.png 465w, https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules1-350x84.png 350w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 528px) 100vw, 528px\"><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">If default values are used for flagIN, flagOUT and apply, all rules are processed, from min to max rule_id</p> </img>\n    </div> </li> \n   <li>Any rules above the one currently being processed are not visited again, regardless of the <strong>flagIN</strong> value.</li> \n   <li> <strong>flagOUT</strong> equals NULL means stay on the current chain id. \n    <div class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"> \n     <img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-108417\" class=\"wp-image-108417 size-full\" src=\"https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules2.png\" alt=\"Ruleset leveraging flagIN and flagOUT\" width=\"625\" height=\"128\" srcset=\"https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules2.png 625w, https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules2-465x95.png 465w, https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules2-350x72.png 350w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px\"><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">flagOUT is only enforced when the rule matches</p> </img>\n    </div> </li> \n  </ul> \n  <p>&nbsp;</p> \n  <h3>Note 3: “apply” will end rules processing</h3> \n  <p>Regardless of how many chains we created, and how many rules exist after the one currently being processed, if the apply flag is set to 1, no further rules will be checked. A very important detail is that <strong>apply</strong> is only honored if there is a match.</p> \n  <p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-108416 size-full\" src=\"https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules3.png\" alt=\"Effect of apply in rules processing\" width=\"571\" height=\"128\" srcset=\"https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules3.png 571w, https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules3-465x104.png 465w, https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules3-350x78.png 350w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 571px) 100vw, 571px\" /></p> \n  <h3>Note 4: negate_match_pattern combined with replace_pattern won’t work as you might expect</h3> \n  <p>This scenario is more specific, but I noticed this behavior while working on a production solution. You might think if you have a pattern and want to return a generic message for any queries *NOT* matching that pattern, setting the message in replace_pattern and enabling negate_match_pattern will do. As <a href=\"https://github.com/sysown/proxysql/issues/1075\">this github</a> issue explains, replace_pattern only works when the query matches the pattern. If you use negate_match_pattern equals 1, the query won’t match the pattern, and no replacement will happen.</p> \n  <h3>Note 5: IP/Port-based rules</h3> \n  <p>If you are looking to create rules based on specific combinations of ports and IPs, you need to specify every combination in <strong>mysql-interfaces </strong>parameter<strong>.</strong> For example, if I want to create different rules for queries coming on different IPs, for port 6098, it is not enough to include 0.0.0.0:6098 in <strong>mysql-interfaces.</strong> I need to specify every combination of IP and port that I’m expecting to use in rules, even when the port is the same. See the example below:</p> \n  <p><strong>Rules</strong>:</p> \n  <p><span>a) IF proxy_addr = 10.0.0.10 AND proxy_port = 6098 THEN hostgroup = 0</span></p> \n  <p><span>b) IF proxy_addr = 10.0.0.11 AND proxy_port = 6098 THEN hostgroup = 1</span></p> \n  <p><span>c) IF proxy_addr = 10.0.0.12 AND proxy_port = 6098 THEN hostgroup = 2</span></p> \n  <p><span><strong>Incorrect configuration</strong></span></p> \n  <pre>mysql-interfaces = 0.0.0.0:6033;0.0.0.0:6034;<span>0.0.0.0:6098\n\n</span></pre> \n  <p><span><strong>Correct configuration</strong></span></p> \n  <pre>mysql-interfaces = 0.0.0.0:6033;0.0.0.0:6034;<span>10.0.0.10</span><span><span>:6098;10.0.0.11:6098;10.0.0.12:6098\n\n</span></span></pre> \n  <h3>Conclusion</h3> \n  <p>When you need to use ProxySQL in scenarios combining different features and handling different rule branches, it is critical to understand how <strong>flagIN</strong>, <strong>flagOUT</strong> and <strong>apply </strong>attributes interact with each other and affect query handling. Using replace_pattern with negate_matching_pattern won’t work. Once you think about this, it does make sense. Finally, remember to specify each endpoint (ip-port combination) independently if you are planning to build rules based on proxy_addr and proxy_port. Because mysql-interfaces is not dynamic, you will need to restart ProxySQL by using service / systemctl or issuing “proxysql restart” on the admin interface.</p> \n </div>\n</div>","descriptionType":"html","publishedDate":"Thu, 03 Sep 2020 00:04:09 +0000","feedId":5011,"bgimg":"https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules1.png","linkMd5":"ef436b08a6630abecefd9acd46191a14","bgimgJsdelivr":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx29/cdn42@2020_1/2020/09/05/07-07-51-319_0c279aab4fb643ee.webp","destWidth":528,"destHeight":127,"sourceBytes":13710,"destBytes":10674,"author":"The Pythian Group","articleImgCdnMap":{"https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules1.png":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx29/cdn42@2020_1/2020/09/05/07-07-51-319_0c279aab4fb643ee.webp","https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules2.png":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx33/cdn5@2020_2/2020/09/05/07-07-53-122_19f43392a42a8667.webp","https://blog.pythian.com/wp-content/uploads/rules3.png":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx30/cdn77@2020_6/2020/09/05/07-07-52-626_cc4405e6621565c8.webp"},"publishedOrCreatedDate":1599289648301},{"createdTime":"2020-09-05 15:07:28","updatedTime":"2020-09-05 15:07:28","title":"Three Bad MySQL Query Types You May Be Writing","link":"https://elephantdolphin.blogspot.com/2020/08/three-bad-mysql-queries-types-you-may.html","description":"<p><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span>One of the problems with Structured Query Language as opposed to languages like C++, Java, Python, or PHP is that it is hard to tell if a query is good or bad just by looking at it.&nbsp; A programmer with a few months of coding experience can be shown a snippet of code from a project and have a pretty good chance of telling if that code is good or not.&nbsp; Some call this a 'code smell'.</p> \n<p><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; A programmer can tell if the code is legible, understandable, and many times if it performs well often times at just a glance.&nbsp; Want to do an experiment on this?&nbsp; Go out to Github and check&nbsp;out a handful of random projects.&nbsp; Good code often just looks good.</span><br /></p> \n<p><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; But SQL is different.&nbsp; It is mostly a declarative&nbsp;language, telling the computer what it wants rather than how to make what&nbsp;it wants. You can random pull SQL queries off Gitthub or Stackoverflow or Reddit and can not tell if a query is really good or really bad.</span><br /></span></p> \n<p><span><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; Why?&nbsp; SQL depends a lot on the underlying structure of the data.&nbsp; Looking for a phone number? Is it in a column designed to hold the phone number, or buried in a long string of data?&nbsp; Separate country/area code from the main number?&nbsp; Is a second phone number kept in different records, different columns, or not stored at all?</span><br /></span></span></p> \n<p><span><span><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; Is there relational logic, foreign keys, and how are they implemented?&nbsp; Are there keys? What do the indexes really index? Are there any histograms?&nbsp; These things are not evident by just looking at the query. So you end up using some variant of EXPLAIN along with DESCRIBE TABLE to start to dig into things.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p> \n<p><span><span><span><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; Plus SQL has a unique learning curve once you get past the basic UPDATE, SELECT, and DELETE commands.&nbsp; So it is inevitable that people write poor queries.&nbsp; Or they turn to Object Relational Mappers to write bad queries for them.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><br /></span></span></span></span></p> \n<p><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; So on Sunday when I got an urgent plea for help from a well practiced programmer friend who did not have a lot of SQL skills and a new 'to be updated' project filled with horrible queries.&nbsp; How horrible? Well, read on!</span></p> \n<h4><span>Bad Query Type Number 1 -- Wild Wildcards</span></h4> \n<p><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; SELECT * FROM foo WHERE x=y;</span></p> \n<p><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; Everyone uses the * wildcard to get all the columns from a table.&nbsp; But what if you need only a few columns of data and the table is a few hundred columns wide, with a few CHAR(255)s, and a pair of BLOBS.&nbsp; All that data has to read off disk, transferred into memory, and then drained off a network interfaces into an application.&nbsp; The program code in question wanted an pair of INTs and a DATE.&nbsp; Not the several thousand other bits of data being pulled out of the database by the query.</span><br /></span></p> \n<p><span><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; This query, from a glance at the code, was the original core of the program and the proficient programmer was pretty confident that the original table had only a handful of columns when it was created.&nbsp; But sadly the table got bloated and the original fast performance is now history.</span><br /></span></span></p> \n<p><span><span><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; So use * as a quick-and-dirty to look at the data but please avoid it in production unless your really, really need all of the data.</span><br /></span></span></span></p> \n<h4>Bad Query Type Number 2 -- No JOINS</h4> \n<p><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; One of the early developers left a comment that JOINs did not perform adequately.&nbsp; So what did they do instead?&nbsp; They read three different tables into memory and pared down the data within the application.&nbsp; So beside the problems of pulling a lot of data from the database into application the application gets bloated to perform an operation that database should be doing.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><br /></p> \n<p><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; So where did the original code get the idea that JOINs do not perform?&nbsp; Well, on the Internet everything lives forever, especially if it is bad or outdated information.&nbsp; The early developer was nice enough to date their comments and the first version was built in the MySQL 4.x days.&nbsp; And there were JOINs back in those&nbsp; but I do not remember their performance being poor.&nbsp; But in this case this other&nbsp; developer was still around the company and was available for a quick phone call. Yes, they admitting writing the code and being warned by some bulletin&nbsp;board (Are there still BBS?)&nbsp; that&nbsp;</span></span>performance of JOINs was less than optimum.&nbsp; While I was rewriting the query the author called back and pointed to a very old post where someone was complaining about needing to join 65 tables when the hard coded limit in MySQL was 64 as the original instigator.</p> \n<p><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; And they there were other URLS of old, bad admonitions against using JOINS.&nbsp; Folks, a lot has changed over the 25 year life of MySQL.</span>&nbsp;JOINs work very well, support the relational model that you should be using, and put the work on the DATABASE and not the application.&nbsp; And if you do search the internet for an answer to a problem please try to avoid coding advice that is old enough to vote or buy adult beverages.</p> \n<h4><span><span>Bad Query Type Number 3 -- Obfuscated Queries</span></span></h4> \n<p><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; One query was the equivalent&nbsp;of&nbsp; this:</span><br /></p> \n<div> \n <span><span>SELECT (City.name)<br /></span><span><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span>, (Country.name)&nbsp;<br /></span><span><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span>FROM City&nbsp;<br /></span><span><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span>JOIN Country on (City.CountryCode = Country.code)&nbsp;<br /></span><span><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span>WHERE&nbsp;<br /></span><span><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span>((City.CountryCode=('USA'))&nbsp;<br /></span><span><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span>or ((((City.District IS NULL)))))&nbsp;<br /></span><span><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span><span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</span>AND (((City.CountryCode IS NOT NULL)))&nbsp;<br /></span></span>\n <span>limit 10</span>;\n</div> \n<p><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; Wow! That is a lot of parentheses!&nbsp; Looking at the table description had both of the columns being tested against NULL were both created as not being null-able.&nbsp; The 'or' and 'and' clauses to the WHERE were not immediately evident of why they were there. Well, after another phone call to the original developer I found out the third or forth code developer was a fan of writing tricky to read code for reasons of job security.&nbsp; And yes they were eventually fired for writing code that even they could not maintain.</span><br /></span></p> \n<p><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; So do not obfuscate code to keep the next developer from figuring out what you are doing as most times you will be that next developer to work on that code but you will not remember you cute little code trick.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Now the optimizer is smart enough to work out the proper query plan but the MySQL optimizer wants to optimize a query each time it sees it; so writing extra clauses puts more load on the optimizer and degrades performance marginally.&nbsp; Exercise for you -- See how the MySQL optimizer cleans up the above query against the World database, and the query plan <i>may</i> surprise you.<br /></span></span></p> \n<h4><span><span><span>Wrap Up</span></span></span></h4> \n<p><span><span><span><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; So with a little bit of effort on both our parts, the well practiced programmer was able to get acceptable performance out of their software with a promise to refactor the rest of the queries very quickly.&nbsp; But in one setting we ran in to what I feel are three of the most common types of bad queries sent to MySQL servers, or other database servers.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><br /></span></span></span></p> \n<p><span><br /></span></p> \n<div class=\"blogger-post-footer\">\n All opinions expressed in this blog are those of Dave Stokes who is actually amazed to find anyone else agreeing with him\n</div>","descriptionType":"html","publishedDate":"Mon, 31 Aug 2020 18:01:00 class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\">\n <!--[if !supportLists]--><span><span><span>1.<span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </span></span></span>What is Dump Load features all about.<p></p></span></p> \n<p \n</div> \n<div>\n <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><p></p></p>\n</div> \n<h3>Features of Load Dump</h3> \n<h1><p></p></h1> \n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"MsoTableGrid\">\n <tbody>\n  <tr> \n   <td valign=\"top\" width=\"471\"> <p class=\"MsoListParagraph\">\n     <!--[if !supportLists]--><span>·<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span>\n     <!--[endif]-->You can customize the import with further options in the dump loading utility:<p></p></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><p>&nbsp;</p><span>·<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span>You can select individual tables or schemas to import or to exclude from the import.</span></p> <p class=\"MsoListParagraph\"><p></p></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><p>&nbsp;</p><span>·<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span>Users and their roles and grants are excluded by default, but you can choose to import them.</span></p> <p class=\"MsoListParagraph\"><p></p></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><p>&nbsp;</p><span>·<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span>You can choose to skip binary logging on the target MySQL instance during the course of the import using a SET sql_log_bin=0 statement.</span></p> <p class=\"MsoListParagraph\"><p></p></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><p>&nbsp;</p><span>·<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><span>You can carry out a dry run with your chosen set of dump loading options to show what actions system variable must be set to ON<p></p></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>FIX<b>:-</b> </span><span><b>MySQL&nbsp; localhost:33060+ ssl&nbsp; JS &gt; \\sql set global local_infile=1;</b></span></p> <p <p></p> </td> \n  </tr>\n </tbody>\n</table> \n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\"><span>d</span></p> \n<h3>Conclusion</h3> \n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"MsoTableGrid\">\n <tbody>\n  <tr> \n   <td valign=\"top\" width=\"471\"> <h3><p>&nbsp;</p></h3> <h1><p></p></h1> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">Shell makes MySQL easier to use, by providing an interactive MySQL client supporting SQL, Document Store, JavaScript &amp; Python interface with support for writing custom extensions.<p></p></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">And with dumpInstance(), dumpSchemas() and loadDump() Shell now provides powerful logical dump and load functionality.<p></p></p> </td> \n  </tr>\n </tbody>\n</table> \n<h3>References </h3> \n<h1><p></p></h1> \n<h1><span><a You will learn how to use MDS, MySQL Shell Dump &amp; Load and MDS Inbound Replication.<br> &nbsp;<br><a href=\"https://go.oracle.com/LP=98866?elqCampaignId=264795\"><strong>Register now</strong></a>&nbsp;</br></br></br></br></p> \n<p>__________________________________________________________________________</p> \n<p><strong>See the full list of MySQL webinars, including MySQL Database Service webinars at</strong>:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.mysql.com/news-and-events/web-seminars/\">https://www.mysql.com/news-and-events/web-seminars/</a></p> \n<p>&nbsp;</p>","descriptionType":"html","publishedDate":"Tue, 01 Sep 2020 12:38:00 +0000","feedId":5011,"bgimg":"","linkMd5":"68608ace115a52fccb387b218629c989","bgimgJsdelivr":"","metaImg":"","author":"Oracle MySQL Group","publishedOrCreatedDate":1599289648307},{"createdTime":"2020-09-05 15:07:28","updatedTime":"2020-09-05 15:07:28","title":"Migrate from on premise MySQL to MySQL Database Service","link":"https://blogs.oracle.com/mysql/migrate-from-on-premise-mysql-to-mysql-database-service","description":"<p>If you are running MySQL on premise, it's maybe the right time to think about migrating your lovely MySQL database somewhere where the MySQL Team prepared a comfortable place for it to stay running and safe.</p> \n<p>This awesome place is MySQL Database Service in OCI. For more information about what MDS is and what it provides, please<a href=\"https://blogs.oracle.com/mysql/introducing-the-mysql-database-service\" target=\"_blank\"> check this blog</a> from my colleague <a href=\"https://twitter.com/alastori\" target=\"_blank\">Airton Lastori</a>.</p> \n<p>One important word that should come to your mind when we talk about MDS is <strong>SECURITY</strong> !</p> \n<p>Therefore, MDS endpoint can only be a private IP in OCI. This means you won't be able to expose your MySQL database publicly on the Internet.</p> \n<p>Now that we are aware of this, if we want to migrate an existing database to the MDS, we need to take care of that.</p> \n<img alt=\"\" height=\"464\" src=\"https://blogs.oracle.com/mysql/data:image/png;base64,\" width=\"930\"> What is my case ? <p>When somebody needs to migrate its actual MySQL database, the first question that needs to be answered is: <em>Can we <em>eventually</em></em> <em>afford large downtime ?</em></p> <p>If the answer is <strong>yes</strong>, then the migration is easy:</p> \n <ul> \n  <li>you stop your application(s)</li> \n  <li>you dump MySQL</li> \n  <li>you start your MDS instance</li> \n  <li>you load your data into MDS</li> \n </ul> <p>and that's it !</p> <p>In case the answer is <strong>no</strong>, things are of course more interesting and this is the scenario I will cover in this post.</p> <p><span><em>Please note that the application is not covered in this post and of course, it's also recommended to migrate it to the cloud, in a compute instance of OCI for example.</em></span></p> What's the plan ? <p>To migrate successfully a MySQL database from on premise to MDS, these are the actions I recommend:</p> \n <ol> \n  <li>create a VCN with two subnets, the public and the private one</li> \n  <li>create a MDS instance</li> \n  <li>create a VPN</li> \n  <li>create an Object Storage Bucket</li> \n  <li>dump the data to be loaded in MDS</li> \n  <li>load the data in MDS</li> \n  <li>create an in-bound replication channel in MDS</li> \n </ol> <p>The architecture will look like this:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3392\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/246262b4e13ce6de39187ed2b3eba180/oci_mds_inbound_openvpn.png\"> Virtual Cloud Network <p>First thing to do when you have your OCI access, it's to create a VCN from the dashboard. If you have already created some compute instances, these steps are not required anymore:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3395\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/3fdf4b352646e5534ac868f5c07644a0/selection_999_665_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>You can use <strong>Start VCN Wizard</strong>, but I will cover the VPN later in this article. So let's just use <strong>Create VCN</strong>:</p> <p>We need a name and a CIDR Block, we use <strong>10.0.0.0/16</strong>:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3396\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/cb6f6dc2f33ba60f42ba3a8f1da33f4e/selection_999_666_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>This is what it looks like:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3397\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/4791021057467cdddbf66914689b0f22/selection_999_667_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Now we click on the name (<strong>lefred_vcn</strong> in my case) and we need to create two subnets:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3399\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/2bc9bafbc9595423fa3c43fe80f03947/selection_999_668_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>We will create the public one on <strong>10.0.0.0/24</strong>:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3400\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/f755d8e39e3ed0575259dddf6d8ea591/selection_999_669_.png\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3401\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/c53fe0935f912676d4ade43e1b9f332e/selection_999_670_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>and the Private one on <strong>10.0.1.0/24</strong>.</p> <p>After these two steps, we have something like this:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3402\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/58edf7c6a254462af85bc2de014f2793/selection_999_671_.png\"> &nbsp; MySQL Database Service Instance <p>We can create a MDS instance:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3364\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/d1e73a1e0e674f6e4fc969c53fbc4a6e/selection_999_624_.png\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3365\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/3ff52f462b87520fe9d2fff1b81c58ec/selection_999_646_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>And we just follow the creation wizard that is very simple:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3366\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/d9180f871d203e7f3a79a94c72b0dda0/selection_999_621_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>It's very important to create an admin user (the name can be what you want) and don't forget the password. We put our service in the private subnet we just created.</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3367\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/4e668586f1ab13a692dd0e210ee45707/selection_999_622_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>The last screen of the wizard is related to the automatic backups:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3368\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/143e03060c239d57661dbab0ff9e4daf/selection_999_623_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>The MDS instance will be provisioned after a short time and you can see that in its detailed view:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3403\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/a3df0e991c0da5366f3a3d3381b3b5d7/selection_999_672_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> VPN <p>OCI allows you to very easily create IPSEC VPN's with all enterprise level hardware that are used in the industry. Unfortunately I don't have such opportunity at home (and no need for it), so I will use another supported solution that is more appropriate for domestic usage: OpenVPN.</p> <p>If you are able to deploy the IPSEC solution, I suggest you to use it.</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3404\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/7dcf0630514b77472e754b1af9cab136/selection_999_674_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>On that new page, you have a link to the Marketplace where you can deploy a compute instance to act as OpenVPN server:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3405\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/0968ad23547dbeaccbf997296d27718e/selection_999_664_.png\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3406\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/aa9577ef44e09dfa0cb38eda90da2c42/selection_999_675_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>You need to follow the wizard and make sure to use the vcn we created and the public subnet:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3408\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/2ee40bd19c91f134c4374686fe973d08/selection_999_676_.png\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3409\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/7bac95c1d130cfa4fef5bc9f85876bee/selection_999_677_.png\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3410\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/9e217a9b11a7a19d0595aa9cd70af254/selection_999_678_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>The compute instance will be launched by Terraform. When done we will be able to reach the OpenVPN web interface using the public IP that was assigned to this compute instance using the credentials we entered in the wizard:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3411\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/e5eeb012c9b7b57de9b4f2bf6eee9031/selection_999_679_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>In case you lost those logs, the ip is available in the <strong>Compute-&gt;Instances</strong> page:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3412\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/dca1f2f5fafc6ec3eb4f14736ce96083/selection_999_680_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>As soon as the OpenVPN instance is deployed, we can go on the web interface and setup OpenVPN:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3413\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/89abd4148ed2ef71b573406f653f0035/selection_999_681_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>As we want be able to connect from our MDS instance to our on-premise MySQL server for replication, we will need to setup our VPN to use Routing instead of NAT:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3414\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/55097984ae1950f5381d72b3f19f02f7/selection_999_683_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>We also specified two ranges as we really want to have a static IP for our on-premise MySQL Instance, otherwise, the IP might change the next time we connect to the VPN.</p> <p>The next step is the creation of a user we will use to connect to the VPN:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3415\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/ab7f8cf77015d7449c9510f3493dbd55/selection_999_684_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>These settings for the user are also very important:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3416\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/dac8dc2835d2993ea651a943741715c3/selection_999_685_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Save the settings and click on the banner to restart OpenVPN.</p> <p>Now, we connect using the user we created to download his profile:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3417\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/f305ff2cda3ea294966ce67e6a35dff7/selection_999_686_.png\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3418\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/c77c0b9da8f262a07a02d08f67a99990/selection_999_688_.png\"><p>That <strong>client.ovpn</strong> file needs to be copied to the on-premise MySQL Server.</p> <p>If OpenVPN is not yet installed on the on-premise MySQL Server, it's time to install it (<em>yum install openvpn</em>).</p> <p>Now, we copy the <em>client.ovpn</em> in <em>/etc/openvpn/client/</em> and we call it <strong>client.conf</strong>:</p> # cp client.ovpn /etc/openvpn/client/client.conf <p>We can start the VPN:</p> # systemctl start openvpn-client@client Enter Auth Username: lefred Enter Auth Password: ****** <p>We can verify that the VPN connection is established:</p> # ifconfig tun0 tun0: flags=4305 mtu 1500 inet 172.27.232.134 netmask 255.255.255.0 destination 172.27.232.134 inet6 fe80::9940:762c:ad22:5c62 prefixlen 64 scopeid 0x20 unspec 00-00-00-00-00-00-00-00-00-00-00-00-00-00-00-00 txqueuelen 100 (UNSPEC) RX packets 1218 bytes 102396 (99.9 KiB) RX errors 0 dropped 0 overruns 0 frame 0 TX packets 1287 bytes 187818 (183.4 KiB) TX errors 0 dropped 0 overruns 0 carrier 0 collisions 0 <p><em>sytemctl status openvpn-client@client </em>can also be called to see the status.</p> Object Storage <p>To transfer our data to the cloud, we will use <strong>Object Storage</strong>.</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3421\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/d5c549032218bf4099ec6426a2293968/selection_999_689_.png\"><p></p> <p></p> <p>And we create a bucket:<img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3423\" height=\"123\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/aae93e93beb2fb99a2e3c4653786691a/objectstorage_mysql.png\" width=\"102\" /></p> <p><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3422\" height=\"137\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/c353eabec0be6a7dd7a640d79e53db90/selection_999_691_.png\" width=\"529\" /></p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3424\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/cf457fc893e682e8b48e20b9ad853287/selection_999_692_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> Dump the Data <p>To dump the data of our on-premise MySQL server, we will use MySQL Shell that has the capability to <a href=\"https://dev.mysql.com/doc/mysql-shell/8.0/en/mysql-shell-utilities-dump-instance-schema.html\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Load &amp; Dump</a> large datasets in an optimized and compatible way for OCI since 8.0.21.</p> <p>Please check those links for more details:</p> \n                               <ul> \n                                <li><a href=\"https://docs.cloud.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/mysql-database/doc/importing-and-exporting-databases.html\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" target=\"_blank\">https://docs.cloud.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/mysql-database/doc/importing-and-exporting-databases.html</a></li> \n                                <li><a href=\"https://mysqlserverteam.com/mysql-shell-dump-load-part-1-demo/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" target=\"_blank\">https://mysqlserverteam.com/mysql-shell-dump-load-part-1-demo/</a></li> \n                                <li><a href=\"https://mysqlserverteam.com/mysql-shell-dump-load-part-2-benchmarks/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" target=\"_blank\">https://mysqlserverteam.com/mysql-shell-dump-load-part-2-benchmarks/</a></li> \n                                <li><a href=\"https://mysqlserverteam.com/mysql-shell-dump-load-part-3-load-dump/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" target=\"_blank\">https://mysqlserverteam.com/mysql-shell-dump-load-part-3-load-dump/</a></li> \n                                <li><a href=\"https://mysqlserverteam.com/mysql-shell-8-0-21-speeding-up-the-dump-process/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" target=\"_blank\">https://mysqlserverteam.com/mysql-shell-8-0-21-speeding-up-the-dump-process/</a></li> \n                               </ul> OCI Config <p>The first step is to create an OCI config file that will look like this:</p> [DEFAULT] user=ocid1.user.oc1..xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx fingerprint=xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx key_file=/home/lefred/oci_api_key.pem tenancy=ocid1.tenancy.oc1..xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx compartment=ocid1.compartment.oc1..xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx region=us-ashburn-1 <p>The user information and key can be found under the<strong> Identity</strong> section:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3427\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/dc65fbecd8bd07846ac3a247a411361d/selection_999_693_.png\"><p>Please refer to <a href=\"https://docs.cloud.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/API/Concepts/apisigningkey.htm#two\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" target=\"_blank\">this manual page</a> to generate a PEM key.</p> <p>Now that we have an oci config file (called <em>oci.config</em> in my case), we need to verify that our current MySQL server is using GTID:</p> on-premise mysql&gt; select @@gtid_mode; +-------------+ | @@gtid_mode | +-------------+ | OFF | +-------------+ 1 row in set (0.00 sec) <p>By default GTID mode is disabled and we need to enable it. To be able to perform this operation without restarting the MySQL instance, this is how to proceed:</p> on-premise mysql&gt; SET PERSIST server_id=1; on-premise mysql&gt; SET PERSIST enforce_gtid_consistency=true; on-premise mysql&gt; SET PERSIST gtid_mode=off_permissive; on-premise mysql&gt; SET PERSIST gtid_mode=on_permissive; on-premise mysql&gt; SET PERSIST gtid_mode=on; on-premise mysql&gt; select @@gtid_mode; +-------------+ | @@gtid_mode | +-------------+ | ON | +-------------+ Routing &amp; Security <p>We need to add some routing and firewall rules to our VCN to allow the traffic from and to the VPN.</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3433\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/2f067124c380a33def334eb3cc6e0cad/selection_999_699_.png\"><p><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3434\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/5aab1d0543027037992cb080ed22444a/selection_999_700_.png\" /></p> <p>Please note that <strong>10.0.0.11</strong> is the private IP of the <strong>OpenVPN</strong> Compute Instance.</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3431\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/d3a8b73387e682f4c87655976c7285f3/selection_999_696_.png\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3432\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/99d3839da4598c10c5e32c69aa2fcdab/selection_999_697_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>On the <strong>Default Security List for lefred_vcn</strong> we also need to allow connections to MySQL ports. We will use them later to connect to the on-premise MySQL Server from our MDS instance:</p> <p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/130566b21e937772a45c4a98c0159f9d/selection_999_737_.png\" /></p> <p>Now that we dealt with routing and security, it's time to dump the data to Object Store by connecting MySQL Shell to our on-premise server and use<strong> util.dumpInstance()</strong>:</p> $ mysqlsh MySQL JS &gt; \\c root@localhost [...] MySQL localhost:33060+ ssl JS &gt; util.dumpInstance('onpremise', {ociConfigFile: \"oci.config\", osBucketName: \"lefred_bucket\", osNamespace: \"xxxxxxxxxxxx\",threads: 4, ocimds: true, compatibility: [\"strip_restricted_grants\", \"strip_definers\"]}) <p>You can also find more info on <a href=\"https://docs.cloud.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/mysql-database/doc/importing-and-exporting-databases.html\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" target=\"_blank\">this MDS manual page</a>.</p> Load the data in MDS <p>The data is now already in the cloud and we need to load it in our MDS instance.</p> <p>We first connect to our MDS instance using Shell. We could use a compute instance in the public subnet or the VPN we created. I will use the second option:</p> MySQL localhost:33060+ ssl JS &gt; \\c admin@10.0.1.11 Creating a session to 'admin@10.0.1.11' Fetching schema names for autocompletion… Press ^C to stop. Closing old connection… Your MySQL connection id is 283 (X protocol) Server version: 8.0.21-u1-cloud MySQL Enterprise - Cloud No default schema selected; type \\use to set one. <p>It's time to load the data from Object Storage to MDS:</p> MySQL 10.0.1.11:33060+ ssl JS &gt; util.loadDump('onpremise', {ociConfigFile: \"oci.config\", osBucketName: \"lefred_bucket\", osNamespace: \"xxxxxxxxxxxx\",threads: 4}) Loading DDL and Data from OCI ObjectStorage bucket=lefred_bucket, prefix='onpremise' using 4 threads. Target is MySQL 8.0.21-u1-cloud. Dump was produced from MySQL 8.0.21 Checking for pre-existing objects… Executing common preamble SQL Executing DDL script for schema employees Executing DDL script for employees.departments Executing DDL script for employees.salaries Executing DDL script for employees.dept_manager Executing DDL script for employees.dept_emp Executing DDL script for employees.titles Executing DDL script for employees.employees Executing DDL script for employees.current_dept_emp Executing DDL script for employees.dept_emp_latest_date [Worker002] employees@dept_emp@@0.tsv.zst: Records: 331603 Deleted: 0 Skipped: 0 Warnings: 0 [Worker002] employees@dept_manager@@0.tsv.zst: Records: 24 Deleted: 0 Skipped: 0 Warnings: 0 [Worker003] employees@titles@@0.tsv.zst: Records: 443308 Deleted: 0 Skipped: 0 Warnings: 0 [Worker000] employees@employees@@0.tsv.zst: Records: 300024 Deleted: 0 Skipped: 0 Warnings: 0 [Worker002] employees@departments@@0.tsv.zst: Records: 9 Deleted: 0 Skipped: 0 Warnings: 0 [Worker001] employees@salaries@@0.tsv.zst: Records: 2844047 Deleted: 0 Skipped: 0 Warnings: 0 Executing common postamble SQL 6 chunks (3.92M rows, 141.50 MB) for 6 tables in 1 schemas were loaded in 5 min 28 sec (avg throughput 431.39 KB/s) 0 warnings were reported during the load. <p>We still need to set the GTID purged information from when the dump was taken.</p> <p>In MDS, this operation can be achieved calling a dedicated procedure called <strong>sys.set_gtid_purged()</strong></p> <p>Now let's find the value we need to add there. The value of GTID executed from the dump is written in the file <strong>@.json</strong>. This file is located in Object Storage and we need to retrieve it:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3429\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/68d6ae992caaa389c0b3fdffa1da20e5/selection_999_695_.png\"><p>When you have the value of <em>gtidExecuted </em>in that file you can set it in MDS:</p> MySQL 10.0.1.11:33060+ ssl SQL &gt; call sys.set_gtid_purged(\"ae82914d-e096-11ea-8a7a-08002718d305:1\") In-bound Replication <p>Before stopping our production server running MySQL on premise, we need to resync the data. We also need to be sure we have moved everything we need to the cloud (applications, etc...) and certainly run some tests. This can take some time and during that time we want to keep the data up to date. We will then use replication from on-premise to MDS.</p> Replication user creation <p>On the production MySQL (the one still on-premise), we need to create a user dedicated to replication:</p> mysql&gt; CREATE USER 'repl'@'10.0.1.%' IDENTIFIED BY 'C0mpl1c4t3d!Paddw0rd' REQUIRE SSL; mysql&gt; GRANT REPLICATION SLAVE ON *.* TO 'repl'@'10.0.1.%'; Creation of the replication channel <p>We go back on OCI's dashboard and in our MDS instance's details page, we click on <strong>Channels</strong>:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3371\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/220f7cf8bee31400a49a2e50b5aeb3e7/selection_999_647_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>We now create a channel and follow the wizard:</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3372\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/d1caed29c3155e48dd7f0cc078ed5aa8/selection_999_648_.png\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3373\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/3f6f4092b3755e0b449285c95b576443/selection_999_626_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>We use the credentials we just created and as hostname we put the IP of our OpenVPN client: <strong>172.27.232.134</strong></p> <p>After a little while, the channel will be created and in MySQL Shell when connected to your MDS instance, you can see that replication is running.</p> <img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3435\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/4b674f37-c893-4139-9101-7643ca30cb7d/Image/035ef85e514fe2f2237ff283af056eb4/selection_999_701_.png\"><p>&nbsp;</p> <p>Wooohooo it works ! \\o/</p> Conclusion <p>As you can see, transferring the data and creating a replication channel from on-premise to MDS is easy. The most complicated part is the VPN and dealing with the network, but straightforward for a sysadmin. This is a task that you have to do only once and it's the price to pay to have a more secure environment.</p> cdn69@2020_1/2020/09/05/07-07-52-643_aecfd69f7889dab6.webp"},"publishedOrCreatedDate":1599289648433},{"createdTime":"2020-09-05 15:07:28","updatedTime":"2020-09-05 15:07:28","title":"Introducing the MySQL Database Service","link":"https://blogs.oracle.com/mysql/introducing-the-mysql-database-service","description":"<p>The MySQL team is thrilled to introduce the MySQL Database Service in the Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI), the only service 100% developed, managed, and supported by the MySQL Team.</p> \n<p>For those not familiar with MySQL Database Service, it is the same MySQL you know and use, now available in the cloud as a fully-managed service running on Oracle Generation 2 Cloud Infrastructure. It automates time-consuming tasks such as MySQL instances provisioning, patches and upgrades, and backups and restores. Users can easily scale MySQL, monitor cloud resources, and implement security best practices to meet regulatory requirements. Customer applications simply access the MySQL databases via standard MySQL protocols. The typical administrative tasks are automated, integrated, and accessible via the OCI web console, REST API, CLI, or DevOps tools.</p> \n<p>The MySQL Database Service is available in multiple OCI Regions and quickly expanding to meet your data governance and location requirements. More data center regions are on the way, stay tuned.</p> Built by the MySQL Engineering Team \n<p>One of the biggest advantages of the MySQL Database Service is that it is developed, managed, and supported by the MySQL Engineering Team. Let’s take a look at why this is so important.</p> \n<ul> \n <li>MySQL Database Service is developed and maintained by the same team that develops MySQL Community and Enterprise Editions.</li> \n <li>The service is always up-to-date with the latest MySQL Server release and includes the latest security fixes.</li> \n <li>You get all the features available in the MySQL Server, including the NoSQL Document Store with the new X-Protocol and X DevAPI.</li> \n <li>MySQL Database Service has built-in default configurations recommended by the MySQL experts for the best performance while keeping the database secure and stable. The configuration management feature also allows advanced users to customize configurations safely.</li> \n <li>Because the same MySQL Server is used in the cloud, on-premises, and for hybrid deployments, you get maximum flexibility for your deployment strategy.</li> \n <li>Customers can use MySQL native replication and MySQL Shell to quickly and easily move workloads to the cloud.</li> \n <li>Unlike other Cloud Database services that offer limited MySQL support, the MySQL Database Service is backed by the MySQL Support Team at no additional cost.</li> \n <li>MySQL Database Service is built on top of Oracle Cloud Infrastructure as an ultra-secure native service, leveraging the benefits of a Cloud that is architected and designed to run mission-critical Enterprise workloads and databases.</li> \n</ul> Pricing: Amazon RDS Costs 3.6x More \n<p>MySQL Database Service is the most affordable database service among the major cloud providers – Amazon RDS, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud SQL. Amazon RDS is 3.6x more expensive than MySQL Database Service. Comparisons with other public cloud services are available below, along with the configuration that was used for comparison.</p> \n<p><img alt=\"MySQL Database Service 1 Year TCO\" src=\"https://cdn.app.compendium.com/uploads/user/e7c690e8-6ff9-102a-ac6d-e4aebca50425/709277e6-520c-4c92-9988-c53470981242/Image/f6b412dd27e4a101d243664fc5e76cbf/pricing.png\"><br> MySQL Database Service: Standard E2 AMD 8GB/Core, all regions have the same price.<br> Amazon RDS: Intel M5 8GB/Core, AWS US East.<br> Azure: General Purpose Intel 10GB/Core, MS Azure US-East.<br> Google: N1 Standard Intel 7.5GB/Core, GCP Northern Virginia.<br> Configuration: 100 OCPUs, 1 TB Storage.</br></br></br></br></br></img></p> \n<p>It is also important to note that MySQL Database Service has the same price for all OCI regions while other services may have a significantly higher price for different regions. Additionally, users can even realize significant storage and backup savings compared to other cloud providers. You can use the <a href=\"https://www.oracle.com/cloud/cost-estimator.html\">Cost Estimator</a> tool for your specific scenario. MySQL Database Service is available under the Data Management option.<br> The consumption models are simple: pay-as-you-go billed monthly or committed annual flex consumption with an extra discount.</br></p> Getting Started \n<p>Try MySQL Database Service Now. Oracle offers a <a href=\"https://www.oracle.com/cloud/free/\" target=\"_blank\">30-Day free trial</a> with $300 in free credits with access to a wide range of services including MySQL Database Service, Compute and Storage. Create an account and start for free. </span>to Oracle Cloud Object Storage.<p></p></p> \n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">\n <!--[if !supportLists]-->2.<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>\n <!--[endif]-->Load Dump Utility<p></p></p> \n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\">\n <!--[if !supportLists]-->a.<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>\n <!--[endif]-->This is help us to <span>Import </span>the schema from Object Storage to local compute Instance.<p></p></p> \n<h4>More info:- <span><a href=\"https://dev.mysql.com/doc/mysql-shell/8.0/en/mysql-shell-utilities-dump-instance-schema.html\"><span>https://dev.mysql.com/doc/mysql-shell/8.0/en/mysql-shell-utilities-dump-instance-schema.html</span></a></span> </h4> \n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><p>&nbsp;</p><span>How does Migration Work ?</span></p> \n<h1><p></p></h1> \n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Suppose you wanted to do lift-shift of database called “sales” , so<span> “Schema Dump” </span>utility will export sales database from on-premises to OCI(oracle cloud infrastructure) object storage.<p></p></p> \n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Then <span>“Load Dump” </span>utility will import directly to MySQL Instance running in OCI compute instance.<p></p></p> \n<p> </p> \n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Below diagram I have made for clear understanding…<p></p></p> \n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://mysqlsolutionsarchitect.blogspot.com/2020/08/data:image/png;base64,\" /></p> \n<h2>What do we needed handy<p></p> </h2> \n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\">\n <!--[if !supportLists]-->1.<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>\n <!--[endif]-->MySQL Shell 8.0.21 Version.<p></p></p> \n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">\n <!--[if !supportLists]-->2.<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>\n <!--[endif]-->On-premises MySQL Up and Running.<p></p></p> \n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">\n <!--[if !supportLists]-->3.<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>\n <!--[endif]-->Cloud Instances Up and Running.<p></p></p> \n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">\n <!--[if !supportLists]-->4.<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>\n <!--[endif]-->Install OCI CLI on On-premises Machine.<p></p></p> \n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">\n <!--[if !supportLists]-->5.<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>\n <!--[endif]-->Install OCI CLI on OCI(Oracle Cloud Compute Instance)<p></p></p> \n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\">\n <!--[if !supportLists]-->6.<span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>\n <!--[endif]-->local_infile variables must be ON&nbsp; for destination machine.<p></p></p> \n<h2>Additional Details<p></p> </h2> \n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"MsoTableGrid\">\n <tbody> \n  <tr> \n   <td valign=\"top\" width=\"218\"> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">On-Premises Instance Details<p></p></p> </td> \n   <td valign=\"top\" width=\"254\"> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">Oracle Cloud Compute Instance Details<p></p></p> </td> \n  </tr> \n  <tr> \n   <td valign=\"top\" width=\"218\"> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">Database Name:- Sales<p></p></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">IP:- 192.168.1.10<p></p></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">User:- root<p></p></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">Port: 3306<p></p></p> </td> \n   <td valign=\"top\" width=\"254\"> <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><strong><span face=\"\">Public IP Address:</span></strong><span face=\"\">&nbsp;<span class=\"oui-metadata-itemscontent\">140.238.227.33<p></p></span></span></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"oui-metadata-itemscontent\"><span face=\"\">MySQL Username:- admin<p></p></span></span></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"oui-metadata-itemscontent\"><span face=\"\">MySQL Port: 3306<p></p></span></span></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"oui-metadata-itemscontent\"><span face=\"\">MySQL Host: 127.0.0.1</span></span><p></p></p> </td> \n  </tr> \n </tbody>\n</table> \n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><p>&nbsp;</p>Command to Export the backup from On-premises to OCI Object Storage</p> \n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"MsoTableGrid\">\n <tbody>\n  <tr> \n   <td valign=\"top\" width=\"471\"> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">MySQL&nbsp; \n<p><br /></p> \n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://mysqlsolutionsarchitect.blogspot.com/2020/08/data:image/png;base64,\"><img alt=\"\" \n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">MySQL Shell 8.0.21 makes MySQL easier to use, by providing an interactive MySQL client supporting SQL, Document Store, JavaScript &amp; Python interface with support for writing custom extensions.<p></p></p> \n<p> </p> \n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">And with dumpInstance(), dumpSchemas(), importTable() and loadDump() &nbsp;MySQL Shell now provides powerful logical dump and load functionality.<p></p></p> \n<h3>===========Rough Notes=========================================</h3> \n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">So doing this Migration what are challenges has come? what are Error provides solid support for the JSON data type. Make the column of the JSON data type, fill in valid JSON data.</p> \n<figure class=\"highlight\">\n <pre><code class=\"language-sql\" data-lang=\"sql\"><span class=\"n\">mysql</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span> <span class=\"k\">create</span> <span class=\"k\">table</span> <span class=\"n\">t</span> <span class=\"p\">(</span> <span class=\"n\">id</span> <span class=\"nb\">integer</span> <span class=\"k\">not</span> <span class=\"k\">null</span> <span class=\"k\">primary</span> <span class=\"k\">key</span> <span class=\"n\">auto_increment</span><span <span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">j</span><span class=\"p\">)</span> <span class=\"k\">values</span> \n<span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span> <span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span> <span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s1\">'false'</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span> <span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s1\">'1'</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span> <span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s1\">'\"keks\"'</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span> <span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s1\">'[\"eins\", \"zwei\"]'</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span> <span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">j</span><span class=\"p\">)</span> <span class=\"k\">as</span> <span class=\"n\">sqlnull</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">j</span><span class=\"p\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">id</span> <span class=\"k\">from</span> <span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n<span class=\"o\">+</span><span class=\"c1\">---------+-------+---------+--------------------------------+----+</span>\n<span class=\"o\">|</span> <span class=\"k\">type</span>    <span class=\"o\">|</span> <span class=\"k\">valid</span> <span class=\"o\">|</span> <span class=\"n\">sqlnull</span> <span class=\"o\">|</span> <span class=\"n\">j</span>                              <span class=\"o\">|</span> <span
